  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Real Estate and Zoning</h2>
    <p>Commercial real estate in Waterville is notably affordable by Maine standards. The 500-foot school buffer affects properties near the elementary school on Drummond Avenue and middle school on Ashley Drive, but these buffers do not significantly constrain the commercial corridors.</p>
    <p>Average commercial rents range from $10-15 per square foot annually on Main Street and Kennedy Memorial Drive. A 2,000 square foot dispensary location costs $20,000-$30,000 annually before utilities, insurance, staffing, and inventory. This lower cost basis provides meaningful competitive advantage — you can be profitable at lower volume than operators in Portland or Kittery.</p>
    <p>The airport area offers the lowest rents ($8-12/sq ft) but comes with trade-offs: less foot traffic, no walk-in college customers, and dependence on driving customers who specifically seek out the location. This trade-off may be worth it for operators prioritizing delivery logistics over walk-in traffic.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Key Takeaways</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Colby investment:</strong> The $500 million Colby College investment is transforming Waterville's demographic profile. Target the college-affiliated professionals as your core customer.</li>
      <li><strong>Regional draw:</strong> Waterville's true addressable market is 50,000+ central Maine residents, not just 16,000 city residents</li>
      <li><strong>Affordable rents:</strong> $10-15/sq ft rents mean profitability at lower volume than coastal markets</li>
      <li><strong>Main Street vs. Kennedy Drive:</strong> Main Street for Colby proximity and premium positioning; Kennedy Drive for convenience and regional capture</li>
      <li><strong>Delivery advantage:</strong> The central Maine service area is large and underserved. Delivery service to Skowhegan, Winslow, Oakland, and Fairfield captures regional demand competitors are ignoring.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="faq-section">
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <details>
      <summary>How many dispensaries currently operate in Waterville?</summary>
      <p>Waterville has 2-3 licensed adult-use dispensaries as of 2026. This is modest competition for a market serving a regional area of 50,000+ residents.</p>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>What makes Waterville unique for cannabis retail?</summary>
      <p>Waterville is central Maine's commercial hub with notably affordable commercial rents ($10-15/sq ft) compared to coastal markets. The Colby College investment is attracting high-income professionals who represent ideal cannabis customers.</p>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>What is the best location for a dispensary in Waterville?</summary>
      <p>Main Street offers proximity to Colby College and premium positioning. Kennedy Memorial Drive offers easier parking, retail traffic, and capture of regional shoppers. Airport area offers lowest rent for volume/delivery-focused operations.</p>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Does Waterville require a local cannabis license?</summary>
      <p>Waterville requires a local license in addition to the Maine OCP state license. Local fees range from $2,000-2,500 annually, comparable to other Maine municipalities outside Portland.</p>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How does Waterville compare to Lewiston for dispensary opportunities?</summary>
      <p>Lewiston has 5-7 dispensaries for 36,000 residents (1 per 5,100-7,200). Waterville has 2-3 for 16,000 city residents but serves 50,000+ regionally. The competitive ratio per regional customer is comparable, but Waterville's lower rents ($10-15 vs $14-20) mean better margins.</p>
    </details>
  </section>

